		<div class="comment-author vcard">
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/27637f7bd58b3f8d63da12304dbbb243?s=55&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D55&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-55 photo' height='55' width='55' />		<span class="authorname">Interesting</span>
		</div>
				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/2010/04/23/turning-down-netflix/comment-page-1/#comment-40047">
		April 23, 2010 at 6:01 pm</a>
        		 
		</div>
		<p>Nina, what does the DRM matter?  You can&#8217;t &#8220;download&#8221; a movie with Netflix, you don&#8217;t &#8220;own&#8221; it.  DRM matters when you buy a movie or song that you &#8220;own&#8221;, but the organization that you buy it from sets rules around what you can and can&#8217;t do with that item.   With Netflix, you stream it (live), you don&#8217;t save it, and if you want to watch it again you download it again.  It&#8217;s the key difference between services like Unbox and iTunes versus Netflix.</p>
		</div>
